Passing closeable resources around is fine.  Let’s look at some examples in Java SE:

* [InputStream.transferTo](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/io/InputStream.html#transferTo(java.io.OutputStream)) does not close the OutputStream argument.
* [KeyStore.load](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/security/KeyStore.html#load(java.io.InputStream,char%5B%5D)) does not close its InputStream argument.
* [DocumentBuilder.parse](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.xml/javax/xml/parsers/DocumentBuilder.html#parse(java.io.InputStream)) does not close the InputStream passed to it.
* [ImageIO.read](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.desktop/javax/imageio/ImageIO.html#read(java.io.InputStream)) does not close the InputStream passed to it.

As for how to prevent other methods from closing a closeable resource, you may want to use [assertions](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/guides/language/assert.html) in the calling code:

    void readMethod() {
        try (ReadableByteChannel channel = FileChannel.open(Path.of(&quot;test.txt&quot;));
